posts.com: I’ve recently started learning the guitar but I only know how to play a few songs (heart shaped box, mirrors section of 21st century schizoid man, roundabout intro) how should I go about learning so I can actually get better and what are best websites/resources to use. posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>115030197
Did you manage to play Heart-Shaped Box in standard tuning? IIRC the song is in drop-C#...

The best advice I could give you is: know your instrument. Learn how to take care of it: intonation, action height, neck relief, etc. All the technical abilities and concepts. You won't get better at guitar but if you can play on a perfectly maintained instrument it will make playing so much more enjoyable and easy. Guitar heroes don't play on fucked up instruments.

In terms of getting better, the best you can do is pratice. Try to make the same things the guitarists you like do, and practice, practice, practice, if you're self-taught. If you can afford a guitar teacher, it's a plus but it's not guaranteed you'll learn faster or better. For instance my guitar teacher was a very good guitarist but not a good teacher. I know average guitarists who do well as teachers. It depends.
Just practice, practice and practice again. What feels difficult becomes easier the more you attempt. You can look up tecniques and exercises online but it all comes down to practice.

>>115030273 says it all, except maybe the part that says
>Just practice, practice and practice again
of course you have to practice, but you have to understand what you're practicing, be it technique or music theory, just like you should know how to take care of your instrument, you should understand the mechanics of your hands, the strings, the fretboard, the pick/fingers, etc.
i don't know how you learned those songs but i assume a tutorial, that's not too bad, but try to get used to learning by ear because it will vastly open up what you can figure out, i eased myself into it by watching live performances of whatever i was learning, and as my ear developed (not by itself, i did ear training exercises that i found on the internet or made up myself) and my knowledge of scales/chords, it got easier and easier, to the point where i can instantly figure out most chord progressions and solos that aren't too hard technically.

only then is it "just practice"

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
get a teacher and start with a reading method right away. guitar music theory podcast can help you get a bit of an idea of how all the pieces work together. keep learning songs but focus on the basics: playing open chords and to strum along to a lot of songs.

>>115030209
>You will give up in a month
I know a lot of people who did this because they wanted to learn lead guitar parts from difficult songs without first understanding the basics. sure, they could fumble through the song at half time but it does absolutely nothing for your learning. meanwhile, I had an acoustic guitar and I learned to smoothly play open chord to open chord and learned song after song. they "knew" 3 songs they could fumble through and I could play 50 tunes without breaking a sweat. then people were begging my to play rhythm and do vocals in their bands because I could entertain and play lots of songs. those other guys gave up after 6 months because of the lack of progress.

basics, OP. justinguitar is a good resource for learning basics and has some decent song suggestions but a teacher is the #1 thing you can do to get better. play songs and lots of them. sing along as well.

It's a zeuhl chart. Zeuhl is a subgenre of prog that is characterized by operatic, booming vocals often in made up languages, aggressive, chaotic and frantic sounding composition similar to brutal prog and free jazz. Personally, I love zeuhl and you should take a listen to a bunch of these albums. If you decide to take a listen, you gotta listen to MAGMA (at least Mekanik Destruktiw Kommandoh), Koenji Hyakkei, Ruins, ZAO, Corima, eX-Girl, Amygdala and Eskaton. Have fun.

>>115002134
Coming from someone who has learned DJing and done shows and has been learning production for three years, it's not comparable at all. It's going to take a lot more time to get better at production than learning how to mix that I can't recommend learning how to DJ unless you really have a passion for it. You're way better off learning how DAWs and synthesizers work if you want to produce UKG, the DJing can wait until later.

One of the only few positives I can think of when it comes to learning how to DJ from a production standpoint is that it forces you to listen to a lot of music which helps you develop your taste on what good and bad music is, but you should already be doing that if you're a fan of music. Beyond that it's good from a marketing standpoint, but that shouldn't matter until you become a real artist. Just pick up reaper and vital and go search on youtube for a few tutorials to get you started on your journey.

>>115025024
Different anon here. Any DAW will be intimidating the first time you open it if you've never used one before. You just have to power through some beginner's tutorials until you know how to:
>navigate the software's GUI
>configure your audio/MIDI drivers and settings
>record stuff (after arming the track and selecting the right inputs)
>use virtual instruments and edit MIDI
>add effects
>arrange clips on the timeline
>export your songs

Those are the main things to start with. It helps to break it all down into manageable topics instead of seeing "music production" as some huge mountain to climb all at once. Eventually, you'll also want to learn how to
>manage/organize the way you save files
>scan for 3rd party plugins
>use automation for different parameters
>learn keyboard shortcuts
>etc.

But once you get past the first list I wrote, you can just experiment and look up individual topics as you think of them. When I first started, it helped to keep a list of topics I wanted to learn as I thought of them. It always felt good to scratch off a whole page of stuff that used to baffle me. Hang in there anon, you got this.

>>115019027
Listened to the first four songs. This is an interesting evolution of your style, it merges the instrumentation and melodies of american Country music with the overblown, noisy Rock that you typically made in a very natural way. The ideas in every song don't feel repetitive or derivative of one another, the joyful Country piano and guitar riffs paired with the Noise Rock freakouts of The Charm of The Countryside works perfectly as an opener, Texas Candles reflects a more laidback sound with his tempo and slide guitar solos and A Small Man Named Wyoming follows the previous ideas named. A Sound Mirage is perhaps a song that doesn't fit a lot with the theme of the album. Recommended.
>>115019075
I love your new song. I like how the chromatisms give a sense of mistery on the piano melodies and how the bassline and the cymbal patterns just builds that feeling even more. If I had to nitpick something that would be the fact that the sections close to the end of the song sound like more variations of the idea presented before instead of something new that creates a higher contrast, but to be honest that would damage the easy going progression that the track has. Recommended and looking forward for your new album :DDDD

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
It was my first time listening to AFUT, June of last year. I knew the band had a great reputation among black midi fans, which was the main reason why I was willing to give this album a listen. The opening track's 5/8 riff combined with its warm instrumentation was a great first impression. Not too basic, not try-hard. By the time the second track had started, my aural taste palette was sufficiently teased for me to be excited about what was to come. Chaos Space Marine was great, and the climatic string arpeggi nearly gave me chills. The outro rolled around, and that's when I heard it.

"Billie Eilish style"

I froze. My stomach twisted and the corners of my lips tensed. Did I hear that correctly? Surely an experienced singer and lyricist such as Isaac wouldn't ruin a piece of art with a line that can only be compared to faecal desecration? I checked the Spotify lyrics, and as soon as the photons of the screen travelled to my eyes and neurons fired in my brain, I instantly felt a rush of severe dizziness that lasted nearly 4 seconds. "Billie Eilish style". Absolutely putrid.

Concorde started, and I soon took the role of a trauma victim who tried desperately to suppress their memories. I was able to pretend that the lyric did not exist, and I focused fully on the present. The song was beautiful, and for just a moment, I was able to forget. Bread Song was a pleasant journey, and I regained the ability to enjoy myself.

1/2

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
2/2

Good Will Hunting's sliding electronic opening instantly had me hooked, and as soon as the drums kicked it, I knew this would be a favourite. The chorus came, and that's when it happened.

"She had Billie Eilish style"

I grabbed my headphones and instantly flicked them off of my head before I even had time to consciously process the lyrics, similar to a hand flinching from a hot plate. Previously, I had thought that H. P. Lovecraft's use of "unimaginable, indescribable horrors" was simply an excuse for a writer who didn't want to waste time with long and subpar descriptions, but I now understand what he meant. I had just experienced an Eldritch nightmare, whose sensation has left a permanent scar on my brain

"Billie Eilish style"

Typing this out was not an easy task, as my hands start shaking whenever I recall those words. Black Midi used to be one of my favourite bands, but now it is more than that. It is a motherly, godly figure. It is a Gaia, and I lay my head upon its musical bosom as it tries to "Stroke my dreams better". Black Midi would never hurt me like that, and I am eternally grateful.

Childhood - idolizing Aphex Twin because he makes weird techno music.

Adolescence - hating Aphex Twin because it's just fart noises and autistic drum beats.

Adulthood - realizing that "IDM" is a failed genre and was only propped up because music publications at the time were deathly afraid of even acknowledging UK rave culture, which AFX was only tangentially connected to despite taking direct influence from. Isn't it weird how The Prodigy's Experience came out the same year as SAW85-92 but isn't talked about nearly as much? Because Warp was the perfect way for music journalists to pretend to be interested in the underground EDM scene without actually giving a shit.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>115025776
Perturbator was my entry point too. Actually, I got my hands on synthwave records before that but I didn't get it at all. It makes me sad to think about it sometimes, because I could have followed the scene as it happened.
Later, I saw Uncanney Valley got some attention from a magazine I respect, I listen to it and it just blew my mind. It just sounded so kick ass, aggressive and all electronic, with lots of atmosphere and a cinematic mood too. Add to that Stranger Things S01 just being aired and I became a true believer.
From there I spent a lot of time looking for similar stuff. I know the scene is getting a bad rap for being derivative, but I could name dozens of solid acts with an original sound (starting with GosT and Dan Terminus for Darksynth, and Noir Deco for the more atmospheric stuff).
Just yesterday, I was listening Destryur and it gave some hope for the future, it's really good you should check it.
https://nightwavrecords.bandcamp.com/album/tales-of-terror

>a time in life when things felt bright & wondrous (early/mid 90s)
I see the appeal of 90s nostalgia, but it shouldn't be done like this in my opinion. It should be full-on Playstation-Drum'N'Bass-Matrix memeing, with the same edge (no edgier) as darksynth.

posts.com: Selling England by the Pound (Charisma, 1973) The best rock jolts folk-art virtues--directness, utility, natural audience--into the present with shots of modern technology and modernist dissociation; the typical "progressive" project attempts to raise the music to classical grandeur or avant-garde status. Since "raise" is usually code for "delegitimize," I'm impressed that on half of this Peter Gabriel makes the idea work: his mock-mythologized gangland epic and menacing ocean pastorale have a complexity of tone that's pretty rare in any kind of art. Even more amazing, given past performances, organist Tony Banks defines music to match, schlocky and graceful and dignified all at once--when he's got it going, which is nowhere near often enough. This might not be the right place to request this, but since this is a Share thread, I thought I would ask for people's help.

I'm looking for a download of a compilation bootleg called The Birth of Grateful Dead. (NOT to be confused with the official release entitled Birth of The Dead)
This came out in the early 1990s on the "Unbelievable Music" label with the number UM 033.
It has early studio recordings from 1966, I believe. I don't know if they were The Grateful Dead yet, or still The Warlocks. Also on this bootleg is an outtake from AOXOMOXOA called "The Grateful Dead Meets The Mothers of Invention" (On other studio bootlegs, I've seen this piece under the title Barbed Wire Whipping Party. It's basically a recording of the band huffing nitrus oxide while a group of people in the background chant "Give me my meat") It also has Micky's "Rap" version of Fire On The Mountain, a rather nice studio version of Mason's Children, and one of the few and rare Lovelight performances where Janis Joplin joins Pig Pen.
Any help in finding a download would be appreciated.
I have a friend who think they don't like The Grateful Dead because they've met nothing but the stereotypical "Drop LSD and save the world" type of head, and thinks all Grateful Dead are Workingman's Dead and American Beauty, and I just KNOW that if they heard this bootleg, they would instantly change their mind.

Again, any help in tracking down a download would be appreciated.

Thanks in advance.

Jefferson Airplane Takes Off (Original vinyl FIRST PRESSING)
>Proto-Psychedelic rock and roll
>Haight-Asbury pre-Hippy music
>Your great grandparents dropped LSD to this when it was still legal
>NO GRACE SLICK
Originally, there was only a pressing of 500 copies of this album, as RCA Records wanted to jump on the hipie band wagon, but didn't think Jefferson Airplane would be known outside of San Francisco.

They lyrics to Let Me In are different than on later pressings, (The original version would later reappear on a Jefferson Airplane compilation in the late 1980s Jefferson Airplane Loves You) and Running Around was pulled due to it's controversial lyrics, but would later end up reissued on a compilation called Early Flight.

Once again, this will be up for a short time, and then I'm pulling it, so down load it now!

Pink Floyd-Animals (8-Track version)
>Psychedelic Prog Rock
>Political Music
>Musical interpretation of George Orwell's Animal Farm
For those not in the know, The 8-Track version is slightly different than what has been released on vinyl, cassette, and C.D.

The song Pigs On The Wing is one complete song instead of two separate songs. There is a guitar solo by "Snowy White" to bridge the two parts together. This was done to make the 8-Track version seamless and streamlined.
This has never been reissued either on vinyl, cassette, or C.D.

because metal in the 80s was developing at a fast enough pace that one or two years made a WORLD of difference. The NWOBHM started in 1979, by 1980 Iron Maiden had debuted influencing literally every subsequent metal band, in 1981 you had Venom paving out the way for extreme metal, by 1982 Metallica had released their first demo tapes combining Maiden and Venom into a single thing called thrash metal, in 1984 you had Bathory releasing the first black metal album and in 1985 you had Possessed releasing the first death metal album,

For Metallica, the NWOBHM is as much of a mythological thing as Metallica themselves is to the metalcore scene

I love 90s ads and promos.
There's just this sense of fear and loathing in them.
They knew that the audience was:
>kids, who like weird shit because they're kids
>teens and young adults who were all high as fuck

You don't even get close to that sort of awareness in advertisement, because ceos now have such a warped perception of their audience and such a condescending "you will like this whether you like it or not" tone to their marketing now.
In the past, marketing wasn't indoctrination, it was a snake selling you an apple from the vine and people were frank about it because they realised that this was just how it was in reality.

Now it's all about pretending to be perfect and infallible. That's why you have this fucked up shit with pharma companies forcing their marketing down your throat to the point of controlling censorship now.
In the past that was just unthinkable when I was a kid.
People say it's always been like that, but I disagree. You look at ads from the 90s and people were fully frank about their nature as a snake oil salesmen in most things because that's just simply how free markets work and how we get new innovations. It's clumsy and rough. But at least it's not mere propaganda. Marketing is marketing, not propaganda. People don't understand how that is nowadays.

Hobbies are for people who lack a professional life, social life, and/or sex life. You already have a bunch of hobbies and they have led to a life of isolation. Having different hobbies won’t change anything. Music, movies and video games are probably the 3 most common, generic, normie hobbies among millennials and zoomers. If you can’t find people to talk about any of that shit with, what makes you think comic books will be any different?

You need to learn how to socialize with your peers. There’s no way around it. It will be hard at first but even full blown autists on disability can learn to do it, and I know because I spent a decade working at a school that taught social and vocational skills to literal retards. (I’m talking 6 year olds in 25 year old bodies who can’t tie their shoes, here…) If you can get comfortable interacting with people in person, then you’ll have no trouble finding people to talk to about the hobbies you already have, but it won’t matter as much because you’ll be spending a lot less time on hobbies and a lot more time going places and doing things (parties, dates, events, appointments, etc.) like a normal person.

I know it’s hard to get over social anxiety and learn how to talk to strangers face to face and make connections in person, especially when you’re in your 20s and feel like it’s too late to start learning. And I know how easy it is to fall back on video games and movies and books as substitutes for interpersonal connection. But in reality, it’s something that can be learned very quickly once you get over that initial hump. And that hump is Fear of Embarrassment. Get over that, and your ego becomes 10000% less fragile, and everything else becomes so much easier.

posts.com: Herr Weingartner does not confine himself to speaking of the eccentricities of conductors, but has a good deal to say about the unpleasantness which the post of opera-conductor in Germany generally involves. Nor is he silent as to the tricks which, Eulenspiegel-like, he has himself played off upon the public and critics. He amusingly relates that some ten years ago he and his friend Alfred Reisenauer had agreed to play Liszt's Symphonic Poem "Die Ideale" and his "Faust" Symphony, arranged for two pianofortes, at a Concert of the Cassel Wagner Society. The committee begged that they would not introduce two compositions of the "horrible" Liszt, as this would drive the public away. They stuck to their resolution, played both works, but announced "Die Ideale" as a "Fantasia for two pianofortes, by Franz Schubert (after the 'Unfinished' Symphony, the master's last work)," which naturally did not exist. It was most warmly received by the public, and was generally spoken of by the press as a "pearl of Schubertian melody." Only one of the critics discovered in it an element which was strange to and far-fetched for the lyrical Schubert. The "Faust" Symphony, on the other hand, was roundly abused.

posts.com:
Writing in a time of profound cultural upheaval, it remains there has always been a dichotomy between British and American bands. At least according to their self-mythology, American bands start in garages and work their way through an exhausting gauntlet of battles-of-the-bands, teen dances, club shows and heavy touring, hoping to earn a profile that warrants making records. If there’s a defining characteristic of American bands it’s a proud work ethic and willingness to prove themselves as live performers.

The origin myth of the British band starts with a conversation about empire over Pimms cups at Wimbledon, or when the coolest guy in the art college finds his voice and assembles a cravat-wearing backing band of guys named Nigel and Simon. With a slick manager and some connections, a career could be arranged, in the manner one lands an entry position at Barclays; school ties and all that. What what. British bands emphasized style and cool, and playing live was little more than a necessary chore. If American bands were Paul Bunyan, the British bands were Little Lord Fauntleroy.

The Fauntleroys had an entire industry playing along, led by the tastemakers in the music press, ever elevating the coolest of the cool and most connected to superstar status, keeping the rest hungry and supplicating for attention. It’s hard to imagine now, since there’s not much left of “the press,” much less the music press, but papers like Sounds, NME and Melody Maker for decades remained capable of creating sensations around bands and music that nobody had yet heard, sometimes before it had even been written.

(continuing)

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>115023476
The crowning achievement of this method was the uniquely British band Oasis. Their first album was trumpeted for months by the press as the savior of UK music, and despite nobody ever having heard them, they topped favorite band lists. Their album entered the charts at no 1 and they were instantly a top tier act on the festival circuit, the plug-and-play standard for live exposure for Fauntleroys since the 1960s. A single festival show might expose a band to as many as 50,000 people, and with a half-dozen of those one could consider live exposure solved for a year, or at least until Australia or Belgium expressed interest.

In contrast, the American scene had little that was monolithic. MTV may have served as a catalyst in the 80s and early 90s for bands with a striking visual image, but the meat and potatoes of the music scene in America has always been the touring circuit. Bands play shows, not festivals, town by town, mile by mile, earning attention. To see 50,000 faces live required 50 or 100 individual shows and months of planning, booking and travel. That hard-won attention was eventually reflected in radio playlists, while prone to short-term manipulation tended to reflect the tastes of the audiences they served. If a band proved popular, they would eventually get played on the radio, even if British. Or named the Butthole Surfers.

The differences in methodology weren’t lost on those in the thick of it. British bands often saw “cracking” America as a kind of final stamp of legitimacy, but when the cold reality of it struck them, that their hype ninjas had no influence and they’d need to dedicate months or years of their lives to traveling town to town playing in front of people a few dozen at a time, the stunned response was usually, “what, play LIVE, like performing monkeys? In… in BARS?”

(continuing)

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>115023476
>>115023504
Sure there were occasional feints in that direction. Oasis, for example, tried to mount tours, but booked themselves into too-big venues, and even papering the room with free tickets couldn’t deaden the echo. Ultimately most British bands resigned themselves to being famous at home and accepting that stateside success was something like impossible.

But Bush decided not to sit in the pub with a publicist (and an expense account) and complain about not being big in America. They mounted a campaign of incessant touring and earned their stripes. They played the whole continent, then played it again, then played it again until the radio started playing their music.

And once they had a modicum of success — once they cracked America — Bush didn’t sit on their heels. They doubled-down on the road work that had built their profile, riding the wave until it hit shore.

In critical circles Bush took more than their share of heat. Back home they were derided for ignoring the channels of hype and commerce that the British music scene required of its stars. No surprise the music industry in the UK was incredulous. Bush were seen as usurping the sales, chart position, radio play, and most importantly the money that had previously all been under the control of the clannish enterprises that spawned proper British careers like the Bay City Rollers or Duran Duran.

Sorry you feel that way, but he was heavily influenced by his then-girlfriend (a few years in early 60s) Suze Rotolo, who's parents were famous communists and who was self-described as a "red diaper baby." Dylan was a Midwest kid who was highly impressionable when he moved to NYC, all the new ideas about unity, revolution and equality must have been intoxicating (along with all the literal intoxicants he was ingesting by the truckload)

There are interesting write-ups about these years, I'll try to find something. But at a glimpse it appears the communists and their movement were using young Dylan to push their messages to youth. A favourite of mine is Radiohead's "OK Computer". This album pushed the boundaries of what was possible in the world of alternative rock.

From the opening track, "Airbag," it's clear that OK Computer is going to be a different kind of listening experience. The eerie, atmospheric soundscape sets the stage for the rest of the album, which is filled with complex arrangements, haunting lyrics, and unexpected sonic twists and turns.

One of the most striking aspects of OK Computer is its use of technology. The album was released at a time when the internet was just starting to become a mainstream phenomenon, and Radiohead incorporated this new technology into their music in innovative ways. From the distorted, glitchy vocals on "Paranoid Android" to the computer-generated percussion on "Let Down," the band used technology to create a sound that was both futuristic and deeply human.

But OK Computer is not just a technical tour de force. At its core, this album is about the anxieties and alienation of modern life. Songs like "No Surprises" and "Subterranean Homesick Alien" explore themes of loneliness, boredom, and the sense of being trapped in a world that doesn't make sense. Even the album's title refers to the way in which computers and technology can sometimes feel like they're taking over our lives.

Despite the dark subject matter, OK Computer is an incredibly beautiful and moving album. The soaring melodies of "Lucky" and "Karma Police" are truly unforgettable, and the raw emotion of tracks like "Exit Music (For a Film)" and "The Tourist" is palpable. Radiohead managed to create an album that is both challenging and accessible, and that has stood the test of time as a masterpiece of modern music.

In short, if you haven't listened to OK Computer yet, you're missing out on one of the most important albums of the past few decades. Whether you're a fan of alternative rock or just great songwriting, this album has something for everyone.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Some of it's annoying, but some of it's great. A lot of riot grrrl just rips of X-Ray Spex, and they had one of the best sounds in punk, ever. Bikini Kill are the prime suspect in X-Ray Spex worship, and they were a strong band. There were some great lesbian riot grrrl bands that bordered on queercore, like The Butchies/Team Dresch. By favorite riot grrrl bands were really the ones that crossed over with grunge, though, like Babes in Toyland, 7 Year Bitch, L7, and debatably The Gits (who were more an influence on both scenes, but still).

I recognize it's kind of cringey to say you're into riot grrrl, especially as a guy, and especially because of the pretty awful cultural impact it and queercore had (picrel). However, the truth is every scene has good and bad music, and it seems to me whether we say we like it or not tends to have a lot to do with which bands we highlight. For example, I can say nu metal is bad, but to do that I have to ignore pretty good work in the genre by bands like Deftones, Sepultura/Soulfly, Korn, System of a Down, and Skindred. A genre I like that gets a lot of hate is metalcore, but to defend it I'm ignoring a lot of bad stuff and choosing to focus on great bands within that genre like Converge and The Dillinger Escape Plan.

>>115013545
the lows are actually fine i think. The other effects would still be good though. If you're just messing around it's not a big deal ya know but it might make it sound better.

Basically that sort of effects "chain" is common in contemporary music (Compressor + Chorus + Delay + Reverb), like if you listen to Lil Peep it's very obvious there are a lot of effects to smooth out his voice. It's just to fill out the track and make it sound less like a raw microphone. You could also just record 2 or 3 vocal tracks on top of each other, but you would have to sing pretty accurately to match the autotune notes.

Quick rundown of effects and what they do:
Compressor: Makes quiet things louder and louder things quieter. The level where things get quieter/louder is the "Threshold", and the amount of how quiet/loud they get is the Ratio
Chorus: Makes things sound like a chorus, this is done by copying a sound and slightly detuning it
Delay: pretty self explanatory, adds an echo. try different time/feedback and see what sounds good
Reverb: makes things sound like they're in a room or a big chamber

>>115010884
Revolver is the only truly great album they have made, the rest has to have at least two shit songs.
They weren't half as innovative as most assume. The innovation mostly comes from the studio wizardry and George Martin. Stylistically, they always picked up what other, less known bands were doing and introduced it to the masses.
Strawberry Fields Forever and A Day in Life are the best two songs they have done. An entire album full of songs like those two could have been a revolutionary work, but no such album exists.
The bands that cite them as an influence blow the shit out of them.
Ultimately, they did good since they removed a good chunk of the blues and added a strong, English flavour to popular music, which makes sense given the fact that Britons have a thing for songs. Even Beethoven was impressed with the folk songs around the British Isles.
